          {
            "text": "Oh no, a brake fluid leak can be a bit concerning, but don't worry, we can troubleshoot this together! Shimano MT200 brakes are very common, and often, a leak is due to a simple issue.\n\nHere’s how we can figure out what’s going on and how to fix it:\n\n### 1) Friendly Step-by-Step Troubleshooting\n\n**Step 1: Clean and Identify the Leak Source**\n*   **Clean the area:** Start by thoroughly cleaning all areas around the brake lever, the hose, and the brake caliper with a clean rag. Make sure it's completely dry. This will make it much easier to spot fresh fluid.\n*   **Inspect thoroughly:** Gently squeeze the brake lever a few times while carefully watching for fluid to appear. Look closely at these common leak points:\n    *   **Brake Lever Body:** Check around the master cylinder cap (where you bleed the brake at the lever), the hose connection point, and the lever pivot.\n    *   **Brake Hose:** Examine the entire length of the hose for any nicks, cuts, or abrasions. Pay extra attention where it connects to the lever and the caliper.\n    *   **Brake Caliper Body:** Look around the piston seals (if you can see them), the bleed port screw, and the hose connection (often a banjo bolt).\n    *   **Banjo Bolt/Hose Connection at Caliper:** This is a very common spot. Check the bolt itself and the crush washers on either side of the banjo fitting.\n    *   **Bleed Port Screw (Lever and Caliper):** Ensure these are snug. Sometimes they loosen slightly.\n\n**Step 2: Diagnose Based on Leak Location**\n\n*   **If the leak is at a connection (hose to lever, hose to caliper, bleed port screw):**\n    *   **Loose Bolt:** Often, a connection just needs to be gently tightened. For hose connections and bleed port screws, use the appropriate size hex key or Torx wrench. Be careful not to overtighten, as this can strip threads or damage components. Just a snug feel is usually enough. For banjo bolts, make sure it's tight enough to compress the crush washers.\n    *   **Damaged Crush Washer/O-ring:** If tightening doesn't stop the leak, the crush washers (at the banjo bolt) or internal O-rings (for some hose fittings) might be worn or damaged. These are replaceable parts and relatively inexpensive. You'll need to unscrew the fitting, remove the old washer/O-ring, and install a new one.\n*   **If the leak is from the brake hose itself:**\n    *   **Puncture/Cut:** If the hose is physically damaged, it needs to be replaced. You can replace just the damaged section if it's long enough, but often it's easier to replace the entire hose assembly for that brake (front or rear). This usually involves cutting the hose to length, inserting new barb and olive fittings, and then bleeding the system.\n*   **If the leak is from the brake lever body or caliper body:**\n    *   **Internal Seal Failure:** This usually means an internal seal in the master cylinder (lever) or caliper piston is failing. These seals can sometimes be replaced with a service kit, but for many entry-level brakes like the MT200, it's often more cost-effective to replace the entire lever or caliper unit.\n    *   **Cracked Housing:** In rare cases, the plastic or aluminum housing might be cracked. If this is the case, the component (lever or caliper) will need to be replaced.\n\n**Step 3: Repair and Re-bleed**\n*   Once you've identified and fixed the leak (e.g., by tightening a bolt, replacing a crush washer, or replacing a hose), you'll almost certainly need to **re-bleed your brakes**. A fluid leak means air has entered the system, which will make your brakes feel spongy or completely non-functional. Shimano bleeding kits are widely available and relatively easy to use, but follow the instructions carefully.\n\n### 2) Safety Notes and When to Call a Pro\n\n**Safety Notes:**\n*   **Wear Gloves and Eye Protection:** Shimano brakes use mineral oil, which is less corrosive than DOT fluid, but it can still irritate skin and eyes. Always protect yourself.\n*   **Clean Spills Immediately:** Mineral oil can degrade rubber and plastic parts over time, and it will contaminate brake pads and rotors. If it gets on your pads or rotor, they'll need to be thoroughly cleaned with specific brake cleaner, or likely replaced, as contaminated pads often lose their stopping power.\n*   **Use the Correct Fluid:** ONLY use Shimano-specific mineral oil for your MT200 brakes. Using DOT fluid will damage the internal seals and ruin your brakes.\n*   **Don't Overtighten:** Components like bleed screws, hose fittings, and caliper bolts are designed for specific torque. Overtightening can strip threads, crack housings, or damage seals, leading to more expensive repairs. If you don't have a torque wrench, tighten until snug, then a quarter turn more, and monitor for leaks.\n*   **Test Thoroughly:** After any brake work, test your brakes extensively in a safe area *before* riding the bike at speed or in traffic. Make sure they feel firm and provide adequate stopping power.\n\n**When to Call a Pro:**\n*   **You can't find the leak:** If, after thorough inspection, you can't pinpoint the source of the leak, a professional bike mechanic has more experience and specialized tools to diagnose it.\n*   **Specialized Tools Required:** If the repair requires tools you don't have (e.g., a hose cutting tool, barb insertion tool, or a torque wrench for critical components) and you're not planning to invest in them, a pro is your best bet.\n*   **Internal Component Damage:** If the leak is from within the lever master cylinder or the caliper body, and it's not a simple seal replacement you're comfortable with, a mechanic can advise if repair or replacement is more economical.\n*   **Uncomfortable with the Repair:** Brake systems are critical safety components. If at any point you feel unsure or uncomfortable with the repair process, especially bleeding the brakes, it's always best to let a certified mechanic handle it.\n*   **Brakes Still Spongy/Leaking:** If you've attempted a fix and the brakes are still spongy, leaking, or not performing reliably, don't risk it – take it to a professional.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"inventory\": {\n    \"name\": \"Shimano MT200 Hydraulic Disc Brakes\",\n    \"category\": \"Bicycle Component\",\n    \"description\": \"Front and/or rear hydraulic disc brake system for bicycles, uses Shimano mineral oil. Common on entry-level and recreational mountain bikes.\",\n    \"purchase_date\": null,\n    \"warranty_expiration\": null,\n    \"estimated_value\": \"$60 - $100 (for a set)\"\n  },\n  \"maintenance\": {\n    \"description\": \"Inspect brake lines, fluid levels, and check for leaks. Check brake pad wear and rotor condition. Bleed brakes if performance is degraded.\",\n    \"due_in_days\": 180,\n    \"frequency\": \"bi-annually\"\n  }\n}\n```"
