          {
            "text": "Oh dear, a burning smell from your RX 580 Graphics Card is a serious warning sign and needs your immediate attention! This isn't something to ignore, as it could indicate a component failure or even a fire hazard.\n\nLet's tackle this safely and systematically.\n\n### 1) Friendly Step-by-Step Troubleshooting\n\n**Crucial First Step: Safety First!**\n\n1.  **IMMEDIATE Power Down & Unplug:**\n    *   Turn off your computer *immediately*.\n    *   Unplug the power cable from the wall outlet. Do not try to restart it or troubleshoot while it's powered on. This is the most important safety step.\n\n2.  **Open the Case & Ventilate:**\n    *   Once completely unplugged, open your computer's side panel.\n    *   Allow any lingering smell or potential smoke to dissipate. Do not put your face directly into the case to sniff.\n\n3.  **Visual Inspection (External - While Powered Off):**\n    *   With a good light source, carefully inspect your RX 580 graphics card *without touching anything yet*. Look for:\n        *   **Melted plastic or warped components:** Especially around the power connectors or fan shroud.\n        *   **Discoloration:** Any brown or black marks on the card itself, on the motherboard near the card, or on power supply cables connected to the card.\n        *   **Swollen or burst capacitors:** These are small cylindrical components, often on the circuit board. They should be flat on top, not bulging or leaking.\n        *   **Dust buildup:** Excessive dust can cause overheating, but usually doesn't lead to a burning smell unless components are actively failing.\n        *   **Loose objects:** Any screws, cables, or foreign debris that might be touching components.\n\n4.  **Pinpoint the Smell (If Safe):**\n    *   Gently try to identify if the smell is definitively coming from the graphics card, or perhaps another component like the Power Supply Unit (PSU) or motherboard. Often, a distinct \"electrical burning\" smell is unmistakable and usually indicates a specific component.\n\n5.  **Remove the Graphics Card (If Comfortable):**\n    *   If you're comfortable handling computer components and have discharged any static electricity (by touching a grounded metal object like the bare metal of your PC case first), carefully proceed:\n        *   Unplug any PCIe power cables (6-pin or 8-pin) connected directly to the graphics card.\n        *   Locate the small retention clip at the end of the PCIe slot on your motherboard. Gently press it down or pull it back to release the card.\n        *   Carefully pull the graphics card straight up and out of its slot.\n    *   Once removed, inspect both sides of the card more thoroughly, paying close attention to the area around the power connectors and the VRM section (often rows of small square components and capacitors).\n\n### 2) Safety Notes and When to Call a Pro\n\n**Essential Safety Notes:**\n\n*   **NEVER power on a component that smells of burning.** This is a significant fire risk and could cause further, irreversible damage to your PC.\n*   **Always disconnect power.** Ensure your PC is unplugged from the wall outlet before opening the case or touching any internal components.\n*   **Static Electricity:** Always ground yourself by touching a bare metal part of your PC case before touching internal components to prevent static discharge, which can damage sensitive electronics.\n*   **Do not ignore the smell.** Even if it's faint, a burning smell signifies a serious underlying problem.\n*   **Fire Extinguisher:** It's good practice to have a small CO2 or ABC dry chemical fire extinguisher nearby when working with electronics, just in case.\n\n**When to Call a Pro:**\n\n*   **Visible Damage:** If you see any melted plastic, charring, smoke residue, or obviously swollen/burst components. This confirms a component failure, and the card is likely irreparable or too risky to attempt repair.\n*   **Uncertainty or Discomfort:** If you're unsure about any of the inspection steps, uncomfortable handling components, or can't confidently identify the source of the smell.\n*   **Persistent Smell:** If, after your initial inspection, you can't pinpoint the source, or if the smell appears to be coming from a critical component like the power supply or motherboard (which are more complex to troubleshoot).\n*   **Warranty:** If your RX 580 is still under warranty, contact the manufacturer (AMD or the card's specific brand like ASUS, MSI, Sapphire, etc.) immediately. Attempting repairs yourself will almost certainly void the warranty.\n*   **Replacement:** If the card is indeed faulty, a professional can help diagnose it definitively and recommend appropriate replacement options.\n\nGiven a burning smell, it is highly likely that your RX 580 has experienced a critical component failure (e.g., a VRM, a capacitor, or a fan motor short). It is generally not recommended to try and \"fix\" this yourself beyond identifying the source, as component-level repair is highly specialized. The safest and most common course of action for a burning smell is replacement of the faulty component, which in this case, is likely the entire graphics card.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"inventory\": {\n    \"name\": \"RX 580 Graphics Card\",\n    \"category\": \"Computer Hardware\",\n    \"description\": \"Dedicated graphics card for PC gaming and rendering.\",\n    \"purchase_date\": \"YYYY-MM-DD\",\n    \"warranty_expiration\": \"YYYY-MM-DD\",\n    \"estimated_value\": \"Varies (check recent used market sales)\"\n  },\n  \"maintenance\": {\n    \"description\": \"Urgent investigation required: burning smell from RX 580 Graphics Card. Potential component failure or fire hazard. Do not operate the system until diagnosed and resolved.\",\n    \"due_in_days\": 0,\n    \"frequency\": \"N/A\"\n  }\n}\n```"
