        "parts": [
          {
            "text": "It sounds like your air conditioner is struggling! A unit that isn't cooling properly can be frustrating, but often, the problem is something you can troubleshoot yourself.\n\n---\n\n### 1. Troubleshooting Steps\n\nHere’s a systematic approach to diagnose why your AC isn't cooling properly:\n\n1.  **Check Your Thermostat:**\n    *   **Settings:** Ensure your thermostat is set to \"Cool\" mode, not \"Fan Only\" or \"Off.\"\n    *   **Temperature:** Make sure the desired temperature is set at least 5-10 degrees Fahrenheit *below* the current room temperature.\n    *   **Batteries:** If your thermostat is battery-powered, replace the batteries, even if it seems to be working.\n    *   **Programming:** Override any programming that might be causing it to run inefficiently.\n\n2.  **Inspect and Replace Air Filter:**\n    *   **Location:** The air filter is usually located in the return air duct, often in the furnace/air handler unit or in a wall/ceiling vent.\n    *   **Check Condition:** Pull out the filter and inspect it. If it's heavily caked with dust and dirt, it's restricting airflow significantly.\n    *   **Action:** Replace a dirty filter with a new, clean one. This is the most common cause of poor cooling and can lead to other issues like a frozen coil.\n\n3.  **Check for Obstructed Vents:**\n    *   **Indoor Vents:** Walk through your home and ensure all supply vents (where cold air comes out) are open and not blocked by furniture, curtains, or rugs.\n    *   **Return Vents:** Ensure the large return air vents (where air is pulled back into the system) are also clear of obstructions.\n\n4.  **Inspect the Outdoor Unit (Condenser):**\n    *   **Debris:** Check the condenser unit outside your home. Ensure it's free of leaves, grass clippings, dirt, and other debris around its base and on the fins.\n    *   **Clearance:** There should be at least 2-3 feet of clearance around the unit for proper airflow. Trim back any overgrown shrubs or plants.\n    *   **Cleaning (Optional, with caution):** If the fins are dirty, **turn off power to the unit at the outdoor disconnect switch AND the main electrical panel first.** Then, gently spray the fins with a garden hose from the inside out to push debris away. Do *not* use a pressure washer, as it can damage the delicate fins.\n\n5.  **Look for a Frozen Evaporator Coil:**\n    *   **Symptoms:** If the unit is running but not cooling, and you hear unusual noises or see ice build-up on the refrigerant lines (the copper pipes) leading into the indoor unit, your evaporator coil might be frozen.\n    *   **Cause:** This is often caused by restricted airflow (dirty filter, blocked vents) or low refrigerant.\n    *   **Action:** **Turn off the \"Cool\" mode on your thermostat and set the fan to \"On\" (not \"Auto\").** Let the fan run for several hours (4-8 hours) to melt the ice. Place towels around the indoor unit to catch any dripping water. Do not try to chip away ice.\n\n6.  **Check the Condensate Drain Line:**\n    *   **Location:** There's a drain pan and a PVC pipe leading from your indoor unit (or attic unit) that removes condensation.\n    *   **Inspection:** Look for standing water in the drain pan. If the pan is full, the drain line is likely clogged, causing a safety switch to trip and shut down your unit.\n    *   **Action (DIY with caution):** If you can safely access it, you might be able to clear a minor clog. You can try to use a wet/dry vac at the end of the drain line to suck out the clog, or carefully pour a cup of distilled vinegar mixed with water down the access point near the indoor unit (if available) to kill algae.\n\n7.  **Check the Circuit Breaker:**\n    *   **Location:** Go to your home's main electrical panel.\n    *   **Inspection:** Look for a tripped breaker labeled for your AC unit (e.g., \"AC,\" \"Furnace,\" \"Air Handler\"). It will typically be in the \"Off\" position or in an intermediate \"tripped\" position.\n    *   **Action:** Flip the breaker completely to the \"Off\" position, then firmly back to the \"On\" position.\n\n8.  **When to Call a Professional:**\n    *   If you've gone through all these steps and your AC still isn't cooling properly, or if you suspect issues like:\n        *   Low refrigerant (never attempt to add refrigerant yourself)\n        *   Compressor failure\n        *   Major electrical issues\n        *   Fan motor malfunction\n    *   It's time to contact a qualified HVAC technician.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Safety Warnings\n\nWorking with air conditioning units involves several risks. **Always prioritize safety.**\n\n*   **ELECTRICAL SHOCK HAZARD:** Always **turn off the power** to your AC unit at both the indoor unit's power switch (if present) and the main electrical panel (circuit breaker) before performing any inspection or maintenance on the indoor or outdoor unit. Verify the power is off with a non-contact voltage tester if you have one.\n*   **MOVING PARTS:** The outdoor condenser unit and indoor fan unit contain rapidly moving fans. Keep hands, tools, and clothing clear when the unit is operating.\n*   **REFRIGERANT:** AC refrigerants are under high pressure and can cause severe frostbite if they come into contact with skin. Inhaling refrigerant can also be dangerous. **Never attempt to open refrigerant lines or add refrigerant yourself.** This requires specialized tools and training.\n*   **SHARP EDGES:** AC units can have sharp metal edges. Wear sturdy work gloves to protect your hands from cuts.\n*   **HEIGHTS:** If your indoor unit is in an attic or crawl space, be extremely careful of your footing. Ensure the area is well-lit and stable.\n*   **CONFIDENCE:** If you are ever unsure about a step or feel uncomfortable performing a task, stop and call a professional HVAC technician. It's better to be safe than sorry.\n\n---\n\n### 3. JSON Block\n\n```json\n{\n  \"inventory\": {\n    \"air_filter\": {\n      \"item\": \"HVAC Air Filter\",\n      \"description\": \"Proper size for your system (e.g., 20x25x1 inches). Check current filter for dimensions.\",\n      \"quantity\": 1,\n      \"unit\": \"each\",\n      \"recommended_stock\": 2\n    },\n    \"garden_hose\": {\n      \"item\": \"Garden Hose with Spray Nozzle\",\n      \"description\": \"For cleaning outdoor condenser unit fins.\",\n      \"quantity\": 1,\n      \"unit\": \"each\"\n    },\n    \"wet_dry_vac\": {\n      \"item\": \"Wet/Dry Vacuum (Shop-Vac)\",\n      \"description\": \"Useful for clearing clogged condensate drain lines.\",\n      \"quantity\": 1,\n      \"unit\": \"each\"\n    },\n    \"gloves\": {\n      \"item\": \"Work Gloves\",\n      \"description\": \"Protects hands from sharp edges and debris during maintenance.\",\n      \"quantity\": 1,\n      \"unit\": \"pair\"\n    },\n    \"flashlight\": {\n      \"item\": \"Flashlight\",\n      \"description\": \"For inspecting dark areas like evaporator coils or drain pans.\",\n      \"quantity\": 1,\n      \"unit\": \"each\"\n    },\n    \"distilled_vinegar\": {\n      \"item\": \"Distilled White Vinegar\",\n      \"description\": \"For cleaning condensate drain lines (optional, if access is available).\",\n      \"quantity\": \"1 liter\",\n      \"unit\": \"bottle\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"maintenance\": {\n    \"air_filter_replacement\": {\n      \"task\": \"Check and Replace Air Filter\",\n      \"description\": \"Inspect filter for dirt and replace if clogged to ensure proper airflow and system efficiency.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"Monthly to Quarterly (depending on usage, pets, allergies)\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY\"\n    },\n    \"condenser_unit_cleaning\": {\n      \"task\": \"Clean Outdoor Condenser Unit\",\n      \"description\": \"Remove leaves, dirt, and debris from around and within the condenser fins to ensure proper heat exchange.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"Annually or Bi-annually (before cooling season)\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY\"\n    },\n    \"condensate_drain_clearance\": {\n      \"task\": \"Check and Clear Condensate Drain Line\",\n      \"description\": \"Ensure the drain line is free of clogs to prevent water backup and unit shutdown.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"Annually or Bi-annually\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY\"\n    },\n    \"thermostat_settings_check\": {\n      \"task\": \"Verify Thermostat Settings and Batteries\",\n      \"description\": \"Confirm thermostat is in 'Cool' mode, set to desired temperature, and batteries (if applicable) are fresh.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"As needed (when issues arise)\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY\"\n    },\n    \"circuit_breaker_reset\": {\n      \"task\": \"Check and Reset Circuit Breaker\",\n      \"description\": \"Ensure the AC unit's dedicated circuit breaker has not tripped at the electrical panel.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"As needed (when issues arise)\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY\"\n    },\n    \"evaporator_coil_thawing\": {\n      \"task\": \"Thaw Frozen Evaporator Coil\",\n      \"description\": \"If ice is present, turn off 'Cool' mode and run 'Fan Only' to allow the coil to thaw naturally. Address root cause after thawing.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"As needed (when issues arise)\",\n      \"type\": \"DIY (temporary fix)\",\n      \"notes\": \"Frequent freezing indicates an underlying issue (e.g., restricted airflow, low refrigerant) requiring professional service.\"\n    },\n    \"professional_hvac_service\": {\n      \"task\": \"Professional HVAC Inspection and Repair\",\n      \"description\": \"For complex issues like refrigerant leaks, compressor failure, or persistent electrical problems.\",\n      \"frequency\": \"As needed (if DIY troubleshooting fails) / Annually (for preventative maintenance)\",\n      \"type\": \"Professional\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```"
